		<!------------------------ Main Content Section ---------------------------------->
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<a href="./workshop_list.asp">Click here</a> to view the complete list of workshops.
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				Select a track to view full session information:
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 1:</strong>
				<br><strong><a href="./track_details.asp?trackID=1">The New Rules of Business: Responding to growth and change.</a></strong>
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 2:</strong>
				<br><strong><a href="./track_details.asp?trackID=2">Development: Opportunities and challenges ahead.</a></strong>
			</p>
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 3:</strong>
				<br><strong><a href="./track_details.asp?trackID=3">Online, Mobile, Handheld Games: Taking Measure of Their Gaming Growth.</a></strong>			
			</p>	


			
			
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>Track 2</strong>
				<br><strong>Development: Opportunities and challenges ahead. </strong>
				<br>Never have so many tools been available to the PC, console, and mobile game developer. Today's development options have given rise to near-photorealistic environments, increasing interactivity with objects and non-player characters, and more immersive games. While development tools have resulted in far richer game products, the need for larger teams, bigger budgets, and longer schedules have placed new demands on developers and publishers.<br><br>This year's development track will look at the creative opportunities that exist for developing games for next-generation platforms and PCs. The development track will ask what's selling in the various global markets, what consumers are looking for from their game experiences, what has been gained by the game industry's alignment with the Hollywood and music industries' star-making machinery, and what the industry's design elite are considering to appeal to the game audience. 
			</p>			

		
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.1 - Hot or Not: Developers Talk About What Goes Into a Great-Playing, Top-Selling Game--Including Each Other’s</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 9:30 AM - 11:00 AM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">You’re invited to a brainstorming session with some of the industry’s top game designers and creators as they discuss and critique the games they most admire: What made those games great, why did they sell so well, and even, where these games could have done better. Panelists will also comment on each other’s games and ask “insider” questions that only the game’s developer can answer. Understand how the industry’s sharpest minds judge success, and how they learn from each other's games. Attendees will be encouraged to bring their own questions to ask the panel. It’s a no-holds-barred session, so come prepared with your toughest questions.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">N'Gai Croal, General Editor - Newsweek&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Bing Gordon, Executive Vice President and Chief Creative Officer - Electronic Arts<br>David Jones, Director - Real Time Worlds<br>Ted Price, President and Chief Executive Officer - Insomniac Games<br>Warren Spector, Lead Game Designer - ION Storm&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.2 - Inside the Next-Generation Game Machines</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">The movie-like graphics, the smooth movements of a game’s lead character, the level of detail in the game’s environments, the vibrant colors and subtle shadows, even the rich and absorbing audio tracks all flow from the combined power of a console’s graphics and processing chips. The current generation consoles and PC have already moved the technology of games substantially ahead of the previous generation’s. As one generation comes to a close, questions about the beginning of the next generation of consoles and PC becomes more compelling. This session will assemble the chip-makers and technology providers who have major roles in the development of the game industry’s next generation consoles and ask them to explain their technologies and discuss how the next generation consoles and PCs will differ from today’s. Learn and understand the capabilities of the machines that will lead the next wave of interactive entertainment.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Mark DeLoura, Manager of Developer Relations - Sony Computer Entertainment America&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Scott Cronce, Chief Technology Officer - Electronic Arts<br>Laura Fryer, Director, Advanced Technology Group - Microsoft<br>James Kahle, IBM Fellow - IBM<br>Andrew Thompson, Director of Advanced Technology Marketing - ATI&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.3 - Sneak Peeks: Featuring Jade Empire from BioWare, Half-Life 2 from Valve, and the sequel to Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time from Ubisoft.</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 1:30 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">An E<sup>3</sup> tradition, Sneak Peeks gives attendees an exclusive look at three games still in development: Learn how the pros manage the game development process--how they juggle the needs of their team, their publisher, and the media. Sneak Peeks is designed to inform by presenting a unique window into the game development process, so come prepared to take notes, ask questions, and learn how the top designers and project managers handle the pressures of developing AAA product--then use that knowledge to make your own game development process more efficient and more productive.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Geoff Keighley, Editor in Chief - GameSlice&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Yannis Mallat, Executive Producer - Ubisoft, presenting the sequel to Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time<br>Ray Muzyka, Joint Chief Executive Officer - BioWare, presenting Jade Empire<br>Gabe Newell, Founder and Chief Executive Officer - Valve, presenting Half-Life 2&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.4 - Gaming’s New Look: The Importance of Interface</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Wednesday, May 12, 3:30 PM - 4:30 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">In its most perfect state, a game’s interface should be something the gamer doesn’t even notice. It should be transparent—and it ought to connect the user to the fun of play with as few learning steps as possible. To the creators and designers, the goal of an intuitive interface is ease of use, rapid inclusion into the game, and, often, the creation of community. To the marketers and CFOs, the goal is to develop a unique selling proposition, increase a game’s potential market, and drive sales. What are some of the recent breakthroughs in game interfaces, and what are the next technologies that will make games more accessible, more fun, and more reflective of basic human activity?&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Jeff Green, Editor in Chief - Computer Gaming World&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Richard Marks, Manager, Special Projects, Research & Development - Sony Computer Entertainment America<br>James Ragonese, Director of Sales, Embedded Systems - ScanSoft<br>Will Wright, Chief Designer and Co-founder - Maxis&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.5 - No session during this time slot</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 9:30 AM - 11:00 AM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">TBD&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.6 - Five (or Six) Rules for Creating a Great Game Today</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">What does it take to create a compelling, original, powerful product in the game space today? What are the essential elements and necessary criteria for creating games that entertain and sell? Listen in as our panel talks about the basics of intelligent game mechanics, balance, elements of good level design and gameplay; the goals of artificial intelligence, reward systems; and the importance of storytelling--about the modern rules of successful game design, rules that reflect the changing market for games and evolving game player. If there are rules to making a great game today (and most designers will say there are) this panel will know what they are.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Jason Della Rocca, Program Director - International Game Developers Association&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Grant Collier, President - Infinity Ward<br>Jordan Mechner, Independent Game Designer <br>John Schappert, Senior Vice President  & General Manager - Electronic Arts - Canada<br>Tim Willits, Co-Owner, Lead Designer of DOOM3 - id Software&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.7 - Coming to Grips with a Higher Standard: How Movies and Music are Influencing the Game Industry</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 1:30 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Production standards in the game industry have suddenly spiked--influenced by the rising expectations of gamers, competition among studios and publishers to deliver increasingly-sophisticated game experiences, and an influx of talent from Hollywood and the music industry. This session will look at the increasing importance of storytelling, scriptwriting, musical scoring, character development, and special effects as factors which often foretell the difference between a top-selling hit and expensive fizzle.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Rob Levine, Editor@Large - Sync Magazine&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Keith Boesky, Head, Video Games Division - International Creative Management<br>Dane Davis, President - Danetracks<br>Mark Lasoff, Studio and Franchise Art Director - Electronic Arts Los Angeles<br>David Perry, President - Shiny Entertainment&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
								
		
			
			<p class="bodyText">
				<strong>2.8 - Surviving as an Independent Studio: Alternative Paths to Independence</strong>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDEDE">
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Thursday, May 13, 3:30 PM - 4:30 PM&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room: Room 406AB&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">As game production becomes more complex, the number of teams brought in to complete big-budget games is on the rise. Some of the industry’s biggest titles and franchises, including The Sims and Lord of the Rings, have used the services of numerous outside studios (something you might not know by reading the credits or box copy). In the next two-to-three years, as the art needs for titles increase, every major publisher will have made outsourcing a serious part of their strategy. Using three case studies where outside independent developers contributed key components to a big-budget, top-tier title, this session will inform attendees how they can thrive as an independent studio. Topics to be addressed will include: how are the relationships made, what are typical deal structures like, what should the expectations of each party be, and how you can set yourself up for repeat business. Start planning now for this growing trend.&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
																				
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" width="14%" class="tableRowEven">Moderators:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Alexander Fernández, Managing Director and Hector Fernández, Director of Creative Development - Streamline Studios&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td>
						<td valign="top" class="tableRowEven">Tim Morten, CEO - Savage Entertainment<br>Patrick Soderlund, CEO - Digital Illusions<br>Jeffrey Tseng, Creative Director - Secret Level&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
					</tr>
					
				</table>
			</p>
									
																																	
